FIELDS TO REWRITE:
{
 "title": "German legal metrology (MessEG/MessEV) forecloses billing-grade outlet metering — the intelligent PDU's core value proposition — in the model's largest geography",
 "narrative": "Half of this funnel is Germany, and the product's premium is 'intelligent' — per-outlet metering. But in Germany, any meter whose output becomes an invoice line (colo tenant power billing, chargeback) must be conformity-assessed under the Mess- und Eichgesetz — a legal-metrology regime entirely separate from CE/LVD/TÜV product safety. Incumbents ship Eichrecht/MID-certified metering options; a new entrant without type examination cannot lawfully anchor billing, demoting its metering to 'indicative only' and stripping the differentiation exactly where the model concentrates its weight. The certification path runs 12–18 months — past the YAM window. EED 2024/1791's KPI-disclosure regime is simultaneously institutionalizing measured energy data, making certified metering more, not less, decisive.",
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "German colo operators billing tenants on measured kWh must use legally-verified meters under MessEG/MessEV; PDU-embedded outlet metering without PTB-recognized type examination cannot serve as the billing basis in the market carrying ~1,955 MW of installed IT power",
   "refs": [
    "profile:Product",
    "digest:geo-DE#c13"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "geo.DE carries 0.50 of the funnel, and EED 2024/1791 KPI/energy-disclosure duties are pushing operators toward invoice-grade measured power; competitors with certified metering SKUs win the metered-billing use case, relegating the entrant to non-billing deployments in DE colocation",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:geo.DE",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c9",
    "ledger:seg.colocation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "The reachable share of the German half of the funnel is overstated: billing-grade metered deployments are foreclosed until a ~12–18-month legal-metrology certification completes, i.e. after the Year-1 window closes — a reach haircut the 0.55 serviceableFactor never priced",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:serviceableFactor",
    "ledger:obtainableFactor"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The team's compliance sweep covers product-safety and energy law (LVD, EMC, ecodesign, EN 50600, TÜV) — metering law lives in a different legal family (legal metrology) that only bites when the meter output becomes an invoice. It is invisible until a German procurement asks 'ist das eichrechtskonform?', which happens after the sales cycle has already consumed months.",
 "falsifier": "CE colocation procurement specs and billing-practice interviews showing tenant power billing is anchored at feed/branch-circuit facility meters, with PDU outlet metering treated as informational only — making Eichrecht status irrelevant to the PDU purchase decision.",
 "likelihoodRationale": "The legal requirement is certain; the uncertainty is how much DE colo billing actually rides on PDU-level metering versus upstream branch meters. Given rising per-rack/per-outlet chargeback in high-density AI colocation, a material minority of the premium segment is plausibly gated. [evidence revision: The legal-metrology mechanism (eichrechtskonform meters mandatory once measured kWh anchors an invoice; PTB conformity assessment for electrical-energy meters exists as a separate regime) is firmly corroborated, raising confidence in the trigger premise. But the falsifier's core claim is partially validated: industry sources indicate colo tenant billing measurement is commonly located at RPP/busway/branch level rather than PDU outlets, meaning Eichrecht status of PDU outlet metering may not gate the PDU purchase decision as strongly as posited. These offsetting effects leave the likelihood essentially at the prior with a slight uptick for the confirmed legal certainty.]"
}

